`crates/` is the CTX workspace: a set of independent binary+lib crates that together implement an agent-facing context/enforcement/sandbox/verification toolchain. Nothing here shares runtime state — coupling across crates is purely through published Cargo dependencies and CLI/JSON contracts, not shared code paths.

`ctx-core` is the dependency-free foundation: its access-gate (secret/binary/gitignored deny) is the canonical denylist that `ctx-access` and `ctx-summarize` both depend on and must not reimplement. `ctx-access` is the sole sanctioned file I/O path for agents, enforcing read-before-write and chain-ordered rollup delivery; `ctx-context` and `ctx-scan` both build the same rollup/intent/`.ctx` chain concept on top of it but from different angles — `ctx-context` delivers it to a hook or CLI caller session-scoped, `ctx-scan` drives regeneration of it via content hashing, independent of git. `ctx-summarize` is the actual generation engine both of those depend on conceptually (prompt-driven leaf/rollup writing via a pluggable Agent), owning the single source-path-to-`.context`-path mapping that any regenerator must respect. `ctx-check` and `ctx-verify` are sibling verification-report crates — near-identical shape (capped `Diagnostic` lists, `Report` with pass/fail/skip status, JSON/text output) but independently implemented and tested; a change to one's report schema has no effect on the other, but readers expecting one contract from both should not assume they're unified. `ctx-cage` is orthogonal: the offline sandbox that runs an agent subprocess under `bwrap` with masked filesystem and proxied egress, unrelated to the context-chain crates except as a place those agents might run.

Cross-crate invariant: every crate's tests fake the environment/subprocess boundary (`FakeEnv`, `FakeFs`, `FakeRunner`, `RecordingAgent`) rather than touching real disk or shelling out — this convention is independently maintained per crate, not shared code. A new crate joining this workspace is expected to follow the same isolation discipline.

No workspace-level `intent.md` exists, so no divergence assessment applies at this level.